1. Correct court + case info
Court name, case number, assigned judge/commissioner (if known).
2. Caption is exact
Party names match the docket (including “Inc.” / “P.C.” / “LLC,” d/b/a, and capacity language).
3. Upper-left contact block
Name, address, phone, email, “Pro Se” (and State Bar # only if applicable).
4. Document title + rule posture
Clear title (“Motion…”, “Notice…”, “Application…”) and the rule/authority it’s brought under (if applicable).
5. What you want the court to do (relief)
A short, explicit request (even for a notice: “for docketing purposes only”).
6. Factual basis is organized
Dates, timeline, and facts stated cleanly; no missing key dates; no contradictions.
7. Exhibits are complete and labeled
Exhibit list included if needed; each exhibit footer/label; referenced in the text; attachments actually attached.
8. Signature + date line
“/s/ Name” (if e-file), printed name, and a dated line with the correct local date.
9. Certificate of Service is correct
Includes date, method (mail/email/e-service), names, addresses/emails, and who received it.
10. Clerk-proof formatting
One readable font, consistent spacing, page numbers if appropriate, no broken headings, no “AI artifacts,” and PDF opens cleanly.